AU  - Simpson, Claude L.
AU  - Kujawa, Duane
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/03/01
TI  - The Export Decision Process: An Empirical Inquiry
JO  - Journal of International Business Studies
SP  - 107
EP  - 117
VL  - 5
IS  - 1
AB  - This study profiles export decision-makers in both exporting and nonexporting firms, in terms of their perceptions of the risks and cost/benefit trade-offs associated with exporting, and their reactions to various types of stimuli to export. It concludes an export stimulus (e.g., an unsolicited order from a foreign customer) is a significant but not sufficient condition for a positive export decision, and that important variations between exporters and nonexporters in cost, profit, and risk perceptions may well account for different responses to similar stimuli by these two groups. Present public policies to promote exports are critiqued in light of the findings.
